<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-601-515  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 601 515.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Nov 1990 v13 n11 p119(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Changing faces: CAD introduces advanced technology to the art offacial simulation. (computer-aided design) (Applications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mahoney, Diana Phillips.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Medical researchers at the University of Illinois at Chicago usecomputer-aided design and imaging systems to investigate medicalvisualization and enhance its usage in reconstruction of humanphysiological characteristics.andP;  Facial features can be designedand manufactured, to the benefit of victims of disfiguring diseaseand injury.andP;  Scientists in the university's Department ofBiomedical Visualization wrote custom software that incorporatesthree-dimensional geometry and other algorithms, becausecommercial packages are inadequate.andP;  They include the patient'sprojected growth and development in their calculations and needsoftware that can handle non-linear, non-rectangular shapes andparameters.andP;  Other applications of CAD and digital lasertechnology include reconstructing features of mummies and fossilsand development of updated pictures for use in locating missingchildren.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignMedical ResearchImaging TechnologyPhysiologyVisualizationApplicationsIllinois, University of (Chicago)Simulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>